Deceased","1335–1429":"1335–1429","1340–1381":"1340–1381","after 1381":"after 1381","1396":"1396","1363":"1363","1340":"1340","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","1368":"1368","1335":"1335","1455":"1455","1388":"1388","1365":"1365","1474":"1474","1397":"1397","about 1397":"about 1397","1418":"1418","1429":"1429","Gateforth, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Gateforth, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Riding, Northumberland, England":"Ridingmill, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","Wakefield, Yorkshire, England":"Wakefield, Yorkshire, England","Farrington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Farington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Halifax, Yorkshire, England":"Halifax, Yorkshire, England","Cromwelbotham, Southowram, Yorkshire, England":"Southowram, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":14,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":87,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Ellen De Cromwelbotham was born in 1368, in Ridingmill, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom, her father, Robert John de Cromwelbothom, was 33 and her mother, Juliana Leyburne, was 28. She had at least 3 daughters with John Lacy. She died in 1474, in Halifax, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 106."},"et":{"1368–1474":"1368–1474","1363–Male":"1363–Surnud","1365–Male":"1365–Surnud","1388–1418":"1388–1418","1396–1460":